    essay: ["No rite begins until he is first invoked. Ganesha (गणेश), the elephant-headed son of Shiva and Parvati, holds the office of Vighnaharta and Vighnakarta at once, the remover of obstacles and the one who places them where they are deserved. The well-known account in the Shiva Purana tells how Parvati formed him from the substance of her own body to guard her door, how Shiva severed his head in ignorance, and how the head of an elephant was fitted in its place, granting him primacy among the ganas.","Ganesha's narratives are gathered in the Ganesha Purana and the Mudgala Purana, the two Upapuranas devoted entirely to him, the latter expounding his eight incarnations. The Shiva Purana's Rudra Samhita gives the birth and beheading account. The Ganapati Atharvashirsha, an Upanishadic text of the Atharva tradition, identifies him with the supreme Brahman and the sacred syllable. He is also credited as the scribe who wrote the Mahabharata to Vyasa's dictation, a tradition recorded in the epic's opening Adi Parva.","Ganesha is portrayed with a single elephant head, a broken tusk held in one hand, and a rounded belly said to contain the cosmos. His several arms carry the noose (pasha) to draw devotees near, the goad (ankusha) to steer them, an axe (parashu) to cut attachment, and a bowl of modakas, the sweet he favours. The broken tusk recalls the tradition that he snapped it off to continue writing the Mahabharata. His mount is the mouse (mushika), and the trunk often curves toward a sweet.","He governs thresholds, both literal and figurative. Students invoke him before examinations, merchants before opening ledgers, builders before laying foundations, and households before weddings and journeys. The first syllable of his worship, the invocation Om Gam Ganapataye Namah, opens countless ceremonies. Because he both raises and clears obstacles, he is approached not merely for ease but for the wisdom to meet difficulty rightly. His association with Buddhi (intellect) and Siddhi (attainment), named in tradition as his consorts, frames him as the patron of learning.","Ganesha Chaturthi, on the fourth day of the bright fortnight of Bhadrapada, is his principal festival, observed with installed clay images, ten days of worship, and immersion on Anant Chaturdashi. Sankashti Chaturthi, the fourth day of each waning fortnight, and Vinayaka Chaturthi in the waxing fortnight are monthly observances marked by fasting until moonrise. Wednesday is associated with him in some traditions. Offerings of modaka, durva grass, and red flowers (especially hibiscus) accompany these vows across Maharashtra, Tamil Nadu, and beyond.","Ganesha's stotra literature opens almost every devotional collection, fittingly. The Ganapati Atharvashirsha is recited as both hymn and Upanishad. Adi Shankaracharya's Ganesha Pancharatnam, a garland of five verses, is among the most loved. The Sankata Nashana Ganesha Stotra, drawn from the Narada Purana, is turned to in trouble, and the Ganesha Ashtottara Shatanamavali enumerates one hundred and eight names. The Vakratunda Mahakaya shloka opens worship as the universal invocation. Each text below answers a particular purpose, from daily worship to the clearing of grave difficulty."],
