      "The Vedic god of righteousness and lord of dharma. Witness of all karmas, judge of departed souls, and brother of the river goddess Yamuna. Invoked during Bhai Dooj (Yama Dwitiya), Pitru Paksha, and rituals seeking dharmic guidance.",
    iconName: "Scale",
    color: "#3E2723",
    wikipediaUrl: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yama_(Hinduism)",
    wikidataUrl: "https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q132638",
    essayHeadings: ["The First to Die","Dharmaraja and the Ledger of Deeds","Son of the Sun, Lord of the South","What Nachiketa Asked Him","The Messengers and the Buffalo Mount","Stotras Recited Before Yama"],
    essay: ["Long before he was the dreaded judge of the dead, Yama was simply the first man to die. The Rigveda remembers him as the mortal who went ahead and found the path that all who follow must take, and so became king of the departed. He is not, in that oldest layer, a monster. He is the elder who discovered the road and rules the realm at its end, gathering the ancestors to himself in a place of light.","Out of that role grew Yama as Dharmaraja, the king of dharma, who judges each soul by the strict account of its deeds. His scribe Chitragupta is said to keep the ledger in which every act, good and ill, is written down, and at death the balance is read. Yama is severe but not cruel; he is justice without favor, which is why he is also called Dharma. To stand before him is to meet the consequence of a life exactly as it was lived, neither softened nor exaggerated.","His lineage ties him to the sky. Yama is the son of Surya, the sun, and the brother of Yami, who in some hymns becomes the river Yamuna, and of Shani in later genealogy. He is the lokapala, the guardian, of the south, the direction the dead are said to travel, and his city Yamapuri or Samyamani lies that way. Temples orient his shrine to the south, and the southward turn carries the association of death in much of Hindu ritual practice for this reason.","The deepest treatment of Yama is the Katha Upanishad, where the boy Nachiketa, given to Yama by a careless father, waits three days at his door. Yama, absent, owes him three boons in recompense, and with the third Nachiketa asks the one thing Yama would rather not teach, what happens after death, whether the Self survives. Yama tries to deflect him with wealth and long life, but the boy refuses, and so the god of death delivers one of the great teachings on the immortal Self, the Atman that is never born and never dies.","Popular imagination paints him in darker colors. Yama rides a black buffalo, carries a noose, the pasha, to draw out the soul, and a mace or danda, his rod of authority. His messengers, the Yamadutas, come to fetch the dying, and devotional tales set them against the messengers of Vishnu who rescue the faithful. Yet even here the meaning holds: the noose is inevitability, the rod is law, and the buffalo's slow tread is the certainty that none outrun.","Those who seek his favor or fearlessness at death recite the Yama Stotram and the Yamashtakam, eight verses honoring Dharmaraja as the just lord of the south. The Katha Upanishad is read not as a stotra but as the very words of Yama on the deathless Self, studied for the freedom it promises. On Yama Dwitiya during the festival of Bhai Dooj, and in the lamp-offering of Yama Deepam at Diwali, households invoke him directly, asking the lord of death to spare untimely ending."],
